A first compose file: web and database.

Here's a real two-service stack: a Postgres database, and an n-ginx web server. The compose file has a services block with two entries. The database service uses the Postgres image, sets a password and database name in its environment, and mounts a named volume, p-g-data, at the Postgres data directory. The web service uses the n-ginx alpine image, publishes host port eighty-eighty to container port eighty, and declares depends-on the database. And at the bottom, a top-level volumes block declares p-g-data.

Three things to notice, and each one is a payoff of an earlier module. First, there's no explicit network, yet the two can talk. Both services land on the auto-created default network for the project, so the web server reaches the database by the hostname d-b. That's the embedded-d-n-s magic from module five, and you get it for free. Second, there's a named volume. P-g-data is declared under the top-level volumes block, and referenced in the database service. Compose creates it on the first up, and it persists the database, from module four, across restarts. Third, depends-on the database. Compose starts the database before the web server. That's necessary, but not quite sufficient, and the next section shows why.

To bring it up and manage it, you use the project-aware commands. Docker compose up, dash d, creates and starts everything, detached. Docker compose p-s shows what's running. Docker compose logs, dash f, web, tails the web server's logs. Docker compose down stops and removes everything, but keeps named volumes. And docker compose down, dash v, also wipes the named volumes. Notice that down keeps your volumes by default, so your database survives an up-and-down cycle, and only down dash v deletes it. That one file, checked into git, is the environment. A teammate clones it, runs docker compose up, and gets the identical web-and-database stack.
